occurrences.line_text: And take me for their Ioue, whiles Ioue to earth is gone.
There on the cold earth him now thrown she found,
There did he see, that most on earth him ioyd,
Whose like aliue on earth he weened not:
Such famous men, such worthies of the earth,
Doth burne the earth, and boyled riuers drie,
There where the mouldred earth had cav'd the banke;
Of beasts, or of the earth, I haue not red:
Ne liuing aide for her on earth appeares,
Vnto the earth, and lay long while in senselesse swowne.
That like on earth no where I recken may:
Could frame in earth, and forme of substance base,
That euer were on earth, all were they set together.
Then doth the dï¿½dale earth throw forth to thee
Ne ought on earth that merry is and glad,
Ne ought on earth that louely is and fayre,
Which doe the earth enrich and beautifie:
Whilest here on earth she liued mortallie.
It bit the earth for very fell despight,
He sayd that he would all the earth vptake,
Had worne the earth, so did the fire the aire;
The earth was in the middle centre pight,
And th'earth it selfe how daily its increast,
Doe eate the earth, it is no more at all:
Ne is the earth the lesse, or loseth ought,
Likewise the earth is not augmented more,
For of the earth they formed were of yore;
But what on earth can alwayes happie stand?
Remaines on earth, preseru'd from yron rust
Th'one from the earth, & through the aire doth beare;
Nought is on earth more sacred or diuine,
For which the earth (as they the story tell)
Could ought on earth so wondrous change haue wrought,
Vpon the earth, with hollow eyes deepe pent,
That euer yet vpon this earth was seene,
And now on earth it selfe enlarged has,
The earth to all her creatures lodging lends.
That liues on earth; but vnto those alone
And eke to th'earth his burden with him bare:
And byting th'earth for very deaths disdaine;
Is ought on earth so pretious or deare,
That falling on his mother earth he fed:
Planted in earth, being deriu'd at furst
Of all on earth, and made a matchlesse paragon.
Aboue the earth vpreard his flaming head,
These eyes him saw vpon the cold earth sprad,
That made him downe vnto the earth encline;
And from the earth, appointed haue her place,
And gainst the cold hard earth so sore him strake,
That was to him on earth the deadliest despight.
Or deepe emboweld in the earth entyre:
He him preuenting, layes on earth along,
Her deawy humour gan on th'earth to shed,
To passe all others, on the earth which were:
Of matchlesse hight, that seem'd th'earth to disdaine;
That all the earth doest lighten with thy rayes,
Would be on earth too great a blessednesse,
That here on earth is no sure happinesse,
Which when he spyde vpon the earth t'encroch,
To griesly Pluto, what on earth was donne,
All which she in a earthen Pot did poure,
The great earthes wombe they open to the sky,
So earely ere the grosse Earthes gryesy shade
Which in th'earthes hollow caues hath long bin hid,
With perly deaw, and th'Earthes gloomy shade
Foolhardy as th'Earthes children, the which made
Which of all earthly things he most did craue;
On earthly braunch, the daughter of a king,
To gaze on earthly wight, that with the Night durst ride.
In doubt to deeme her borne of earthly brood;
What man so wise, what earthly wit so ware,
Brought forth this monstrous masse of earthly slime,
Or liking find to gaze on earthly mould,
For earthly sight can nought but sorow breed,
Such earthly mettals soone consumed bene:
Nothing is sure, that growes on earthly ground:
Whose wondrous faith, exceeding earthly race,
The images of God in earthly clay;
All were his earthly eyen both blunt and bad,
Of perle and precious stone, that earthly tong
Yet is Cleopolis for earthly frame,
Thenceforth the suit of earthly conquest shonne,
So darke are earthly things compard to things diuine.
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
Or earthly wight thou be, withhold this deadly howre.
That earthly thing may not my courage braue
But when as earthly wight they present saw,
That neuer earthly Prince in such aray
But I, that am fraile flesh and earthly wight,
That no'te auoyded be by earthly skill or powre.
Or grace of earthly Prince so soueraine,
Soone it must turne to earth; no earthly thing is sure.
And lifted high aboue this earthly masse,
By which all earthly Princes she doth farre surmount.
To be no earthly wight, but either Spright,
Till it dissolued be from earthly band.
He shall his dayes with peace bring to his earthly In.
This warlike sonne vnto an earthly peare,
Boue all the sonnes, that were of earthly wombes ybore.
Good both for earthly med'cine, and for heauenly food.
As it an earthly Paradize had beene:
And did in stocke of earthly flesh enrace,
And doubted her to deeme an earthly wight,
No word they spake, nor earthly thing they felt,
That it could ouerreach the wisest earthly wight.
Began to peepe aboue this earthly masse,
For as the soule doth rule the earthly masse,
That seem'd vnlike vnto his earthly home:
Of earthly mould, and form'd of flesh and bone,
Astrï¿½a here mongst earthly men did dwell,
Of all that on this earthly compasse wonnes:
Where whilest her earthly parts with soft delight
That herein doest all earthly Princes pas?
So tickle is the state of earthly things,
Were downe to them descended in that earthly vew.
And trembling with strange feare, did like an earthquake show.
As it an Earth-quake were; at last she thus bespake.
And an earth-quake, as if it streight would lose
But on their mother Earths deare lap did lie,
And to be easd of that base burden still did erne.
But all your hurts may soone through te[m]perance be easd.
So slyding softly forth, she turnd as to her ease.
Or let him die at ease, that liueth here vneath?
And happie ease, which thou doest want and craue,
Is not short paine well borne, that brings long ease,
Ease after warre, death after life does greatly please.
By which to ease he him recured briefe,
Vnto you bring, to ease you of your misery.
Let vs deuize of ease and euerlasting rest.
Of ease or rest I may not yet deuize;
Her voluntarie paine, and feele some secret ease.
So long they traueiled with litle ease,
Where ease abounds, yt's eath to doe amis;
For to allure fraile mind to carelesse ease.
Some plaid with strawes, some idly sat at ease;
To ease you of that ill, so wisely as I may.
And insolent wox through vnwonted ease,
That he might know, and ease her sorrow sad:
Some for vntimely ease, some for delight,
And chaungd her weary side, the better ease to take.
Such secret ease felt gentle Britomart,
Yet wist, she was not well at ease perdy,
Of my deare foster child, to ease thy griefe,
Beldame, your words doe worke me litle ease;
At last blow vp some gentle gale of ease,
To do him ease, or do him remedy:
Perhaps this hand may helpe to ease your woe,
Ease, on his robe in golden letters cyphered.
He by no meanes could wished ease obtaine:
Yet found no ease of griefe, nor hope of grace,
Ne ought mote ease or mitigate his paine,
That much did ease his mourning and misfare:
Besought her to graunt ease vnto my smart,
She saw could ease his rankling maladie,
As her owne selfe, to ease her selfe of dout.
One day, when as she long had sought for ease
By change of place seeking to ease her paine;
As sundry chaunge her seemed best to ease.
Would change her paine, and sorrow somewhat ease,
He lightly reft his head, to ease him of his paine.
Spake, as was meet, for ease of my regret:
To wype his wounds, and ease their bitter payning.
Doe it disclose, to ease your grieued spright:
His limbes would rest, ne lig in ease embost,
To seeke some place, the which mote yeeld some ease
To guide mens labours, brought them also ease,
Sitting beside his Ladie there at ease,
In which ye father here doe dwell at ease,
Or at more ease continue there his thrall:
Their aged Syre, thus eased of his crowne,
Hart that is inly hurt, is greatly eased
She much was eased in her troublous thought,
And would on her owne Palfrey him haue eased,
Ye well may hope, and easely attaine?
Yet found no easement in her troubled wits,
Glad of that easement, though it were but small;
And brought the heauie corse with easie pace
Three miles it might be easie heard around,
Of puissant armes, and laid in easie bed;
That was on earth not easie to compare;
That easie was t'inuegle weaker sight:
Behaues with cares, cannot so easie mis.
But easie is the way, and passage plaine
So easie was to quench his flamed mind
So easie is, t'appease the stormie wind
The sea is wide, and easie for to stray;
Not wrought, nor pourtrahed, but easie to be thought.
But that they ouerran all parts with easie hand.
Full easie was for her to haue beliefe,
Which whenas none she fond, with easie shift,
Ne soothlich is it easie for to read,
There they him laid in easie couch well dight;
In easie couch his feeble limbes to rest,
So may he long himselfe full easie hide:
Depeincted was, full easie to be knowne,
More easie issew now, then entrance late
But not so easie will I her forsake;
By scattered shields was easie to be showen.
With easie steps so soft as foot could stryde.
By which it's easie him to know againe,
Certes your strife were easie to accord,
That by your change of cheare is easie for to see.
No easie meanes according to his mind.
That to Sir Calidore was easie geare;
O What an easie thing is to descry
Mote easie be supprest with little thing:
To some hid end to make more easie way,
To their deseigne to make the easier way,
And can more easily be thought, then said.
And of his armes despoyled easily,
That he the boateman bad row easily,
Did easily beleeue her strong extremitie.
Into his hidden net full easily doth fall.
They easily vnto her charet beare:
But, as he nigher drew, he easily
That vp his head he reared easily,
That by his gate might easily appeare;
That none the same may easily out win;
That by her monstrous shape might easily be red.
And so would hope him easily to foyle.
To which he easily did them perswade.
Their scepters stretcht from East to Westerne shore,
Out of the East the dawning day doth call:
Scarsely had Phoebus in the glooming East
Out of the East, with flaming lockes bedight,
Lookt foorth, as Phoebus face out of the east,
The wealth of th'East, and pompe of Persian kings;
But reeled to and fro from East to West:
That who from East to West will endlong seeke,
Out of the ruddy East was fully reard,
As like can not be seene from East to West,
All th'East before vntam'd did ouerronne,
Or weigh the light, that in the East doth rise;
S   O soone as day forth dawning from the East,
He Easterland subdewd, and Danmarke wonne,
Those spoilefull Picts, and swarming Easterlings,
And Titan playing on the eastern streames,
In hast was climbing vp the Easterne hill,
But to the easterne coast of heauen makes speedy way.
The Easterne Saxons from the Southerne ny,
He could not rest, but did his stout heart eat,
And the sharpe yron did for anger eat,
Still as he rode, he somewhat still did eat,
And rend his flesh, and his owne synewes eat.
And greedie gulfe does gape, as he would eat
Whereof who so did eat, eftsoones did know
Such entertainment base, ne ought would eat,
Of grace I pray thee, giue to eat and drinke to mee.
And that same bitter corsiue, which did eat
Ne doth she giue them other thing to eat,
He gan to threaten her likewise to eat;
And vexeth so, that makes her eat her gall.
For when she wanteth other thing to eat,
And if he hungry were, him offred eke to eat.
Ne would they eate, till she in presence came.
And of vs three to morrow he will sure eate one.
Doe eate the earth, it is no more at all:
And bid him eate, henceforth he oft shall hungry sit.
To eate the flesh of men, whom they mote fynde,
And then her eate attonce; or many meales to make.
Therein is eaten out an hollow caue,
Seauen women by him slaine, and eaten clene.
As if that long she had not eaten ought;
Where ease abounds, yt's eath to doe amis;
It's eath his idle furie to asswage,
More eath to number, with how many eyes
More eath was new impression to receiue,
Of our like persons eath to be disguiz'd,
The which, more eath it were for mortall wight,
For much more eath to tell the starres on hy,
So can they both them selues full eath perswade
But Ebranck salued both their infamies
The fourth Ecastor, of exceeding might;
That all the woods with doubled Eccho ring,
That through the woods their Eccho did rebound.
Which softly ecchoed from the neighbour wood;
That sent to heauen the ecchoed report
Throughout the wood, that ecchoed againe,
And Ecchoes three answerd it selfe againe:
The woods did nought but ecchoes vaine rebound;
And ech of them had ryding by his side
They stemme ech other with so fell despight,
Whereof full glad for thirst, ech drunk an harty draught.
So euery place seem'd painefull, and ech changing vaine.
And made ech member quake, and manly hart to quayle.
And went both on their way, ne ech would other leaue.
And foule Echidna, in the house of night;
Borne of the brooding of Echidna base,
Begot of foule Echidna, as in bookes is taught.
Echidna is a Monster direfull dred,
To thee, most mighty king of Eden faire,
To beene departed out of Eden lands,
Or Eden selfe, if ought with Eden mote compaire.
Or Eden selfe, if ought with Eden mote compaire.
And Albany: And Eden though but small,
Therewith their dulled sprights they edgd anew,
So been they parted both, with harts on edge,
Wherein he fell, or sharper edge did feele,
To weld his naked sword, and try the edges keene.
There was an holy Chappell edifyde,
Through countries waste, and eke well edifyde,
That Castle was most goodly edifyde,
On his sonne Edwin all those wrongs shall wreake;
Till both the sonnes of Edwin he haue slaine,
How oft for Venus, and how often eek
Thou biddest me to eeke? Can Night defray
Spare, gentle sister, with reproch my paine to eeke.
Th'one to diminish, th'other for to eeke.
She would it eeke, and make much worse by telling,
Three mightie ones, and cruell minded eeke,
That he could make; And eeke that angry foole
And eeke of person huge and hideous,
So be ye soft and tender eeke in mynde;
And eeke this wallet at your backe arreare,
And eeke them selues so in their daunce they bore,
So did he eeke long after this remaine,
Or how their liues were eekt, she did not tell;
Giue ouer to effect his first intent,
Thou doest effect in destined descents,
How to effect so hard an enterprize,
And findeth dew effect or soone or late.
The sad effect of her neare ouerthrow;
Which thereon seizing, tooke no great effect;
Her stubborne hart with inward deepe effect,
Remoued is, th'effect surceaseth still.
Effect the same, whylest all the night was spent.
All which the sad effects of discord sung:
That with fell woodnesse he effierced was,
Them to efforce by violence or wrong;
Yet list the same efforce with faind gainesay;
Ere that we to efforce it do begin:
For to efforce, when charmes had closed it afore.
Againe he heard a more efforced voyce,
By which the mightiest things efforced bin:
To haue efforst the loue of that faire lasse,
And thralled her in chaines with strong effort,
With stings of carnall lust, and strong effort
To loose her warlike limbs and strong effort,
To shew Dan Cupids powre and great effort:
By which he stil them holds, & keepes with strong effort.
Ne durst abide behind, for dread of worse effort.
Their dam vpstart, out of her den effraide,
Eft looking backe would faine haue runne away;
Eft soones of him had perfect cognizance,
Eft through the thicke they heard one rudely rush;
Attonce I was vpbrought, and eft when yeares
Eft to Cymochles twise so many fold:
Eft fierce returning, as a Faulcon faire
It would haue liued, and reuiued eft;
And eft them turned both againe to fight;
And eft auentring his steeleheaded launce,
And eft againe deuiz'd some what to say,
And eft gan into tender teares to melt.
The Lady to alight did eft require,
To perils great; which he vnbuckling eft,
Yet seem'd the soyle both fayre and frutefull eft,
Eftsoone she said, Ah gentle trustie Squire,
Of what might hap. Eftsoone there stepped forth
Eftsoones dismounted from his courser braue,
Eftsoones he tooke that miscreated faire,
Of natiue vertue gan eftsoones reuiue,
Eftsoones I thought her such, as she me told,
He burnt in fire, and gan eftsoones prepare
Eftsoones he perced through his chaufed chest
Eftsoones his manly forces gan to faile,
Well searcht, eftsoones he gan apply reliefe
Eftsoones vnto an holy Hospitall,
Eftsoones that dreadfull Dragon they espide,
Eftsoones he gan aduance his haughtie crest,
Whereof who so did eat, eftsoones did know
Eftsoones the Gard, which on his state did wait,
Eftsoones vntwisting his deceiptfull clew,
Eftsoones deuisd redresse for such annoyes;
Eftsoones to court he cast t'auaunce his first degree.
Eftsoones this liege-man gan to wexe more bold,
Eftsoones supposed him a person meet,
Eftsoones he came vnto th'appointed place,
Eftsoones he fled away, and might no where be seene.
Eftsoones his cruell hand Sir Guyon stayd,
Eftsoones her shallow ship away did slide,
Eftsoones he gan to rage, and inly fret,
And pompous pride eftsoones he did compound;
So hauing said, eftsoones he gan display
That both eftsoones vpstarted furiously,
Eftsoones forth looked from the highest spire
From whence eftsoones arriued here three hoyes
And he eftsoones gan launch his barke forthright.
Eftsoones himselfe in glitterand armes he dight,
Eftsoones she causd him vp to be conuayd,
Eftsoones they saw an hideous hoast arrayd,
Eftsoones their stubborne courages were queld,
Eftsoones them brought vnto their Ladies sight,
Eftsoones she grew to great impatience
Eftsoones long waxen torches weren light,
Eftsoones there was presented to her eye
Eftsoones her goodly shield addressing faire,
Eftsoones his heaped waues he did commaund,
Eftsoones both flowres and girlonds farre away
Eftsoones the roaring billowes still abid,
Eftsoones his warlike courser, which was strayd
Eftsoones her steps she thereunto applyde,
Eftsoones out of her hidden caue she cald
Eftsoones she bad me, with incessaunt paine
His bloudie speare eftsoones he boldly bent
And comming nigh, eftsoones he gan to gesse
Assayld the flame, the which eftsoones gaue place,
Forst him eftsoones to follow other game,
Approching nigh, eftsoones his wanton hart
Beheld, eftsoones it prickt his wanton mind
That cruell Atropos eftsoones vndid,
Eftsoones his life may passe into the next;
But through traduction was eftsoones deriued,
Whereof full blith, eftsoones his mightie hand
Eftsoones out of her Coch she gan auaile,
And vaunted speare eftsoones to disaduaunce,
The which eftsoones discouered, to it drew
Eftsoones he gan to gather vp around
A mightie speare eftsoones at him he bent;
And passing beautie did eftsoones reueale,
Whose beauties beame eftsoones did shine so bright,
But when they thought it fast, eftsoones it was vntide.
Eftsoones one of those villeins him did rap
She gan eftsoones it to her mind to call,
Eftsoones she flew vnto his fearelesse hand,
When so he heard her say, eftsoones he brake
Eftsoones that pretious liquour forth he drew,
Eftsoones the Prince tooke downe those Ladies twaine
Eftsoones the others did the field recoure,
Eftsoones all burning with a fresh desire,
Eftsoones him selfe he to their aide addrest,
Eftsoones out sprung two more of equall mould;
Eftsoones aduauncing that enchaunted shield,
His cleared heart eftsoones away gan chace
Eftsoones him selfe he from his hold vnbownd,
Eftsoones his Page drew to the Castle gate,
Eftsoones he stood as still as any stake,
Eftsoones the people all to harnesse ran,
Eftsoones that warriouresse with haughty crest
Eftsoones they gan their wrothfull hands to hold,
And gan eftsoones deuize to be aueng'd for it.
Eftsoones brought forth the villaine, as they ment,
Her selfe eftsoones she gan conuert againe;
And from her partie eftsoones was drawen cleene.
Eftsoones forth pricked proudly in his might,
Eftsoones againe his axe he raught on hie,
And buckling him eftsoones vnto the fight,
Eftsoones he loosd that Squire, and so him left,
Had left behind, he gan eftsoones prepare,
Eftsoones he spide a Knight approching nye,
Beheld, eftsoones he all enraged grew,
Eftsoones they pricked forth with forward pryde,
Eftsoones the Prince to him full nimbly stept,
Eftsoones he saw one with a naked knife
And eger greedinesse through euery member thrild.
Gan towards them to pricke with eger speede,
Did leape to her, as doth an eger hound
But when his foe he still so eger saw,
And to her ran with hasty egernesse,
Through which the fragrant Eglantine did spred
And Eglantine, and Caprifole emong,
An Egle, that with plumy wings doth sheare
Then at the aymed marke, which he had eide:
Who[m] sure he weend, that he some wher tofore had eide.
Whom when discouered they had throughly eide,
A ruefull sight, as could be seene with eie;
That it would pitty any liuing eie.
To catch her, newly offred to his eie:
The which these reliques sad present vnto mine eie.
Both fled attonce, ne euer backe returned eie.
Assotted had his sense, or dazed was his eie.
His rouing eie did on the Lady glaunce,
His weary eie returnd to him againe,
So faire, as euer yet saw liuing eie:
Whom soone as they with wrathfull eie bewraide,
Therewith her dim eie-lids she vp gan reare,
His cheeke bones raw, and eie-pits hollow grew,
To tell the sad sight, which mine eies haue red:
Whiles through their lids his wanton eies do peepe,
Of hungry eies, which n'ote therewith be fild,
And her faire deawy eies with kisses deare
While teares stood in his eies, few drops of bitternesse.
On which their eies and harts were wholly set,
She cast her eies, to see what was become
During which space these sory eies haue seen
From his moist eies, and like two streames procead;
Ne ought he did, but with fast fixed eies
And from her eies did flash out fiery light,
Which carry colours faire, that feeble eies misdeeme.
Fashion'd to please the eies of them, that pas,
Your eies, your eares, your tongue, your talk restraine
His lookes were dreadfull, and his fiery eies
Which when she sees with ghastly griefful eies,
The glaunce whereof their dimmed eies would daze,
Coulin to make, being eight lugs of grownd;
Of dying people, during eight yeares space,
And Neso, and Eione well in age,
Wherefore the Lady, which Eirena hight,
Iust Dice, wise Eunomie, myld Eirene,
Their horned fronts so fierce on either side
Two iron coffers hong on either side,
